{"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"minor":3,"major":0},"sections":[],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/Playdate\/documentation\/Playdate","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/playdate"]}],"abstract":[{"text":"A technical demonstration of Embedded Swift running on Playdate by Panic.","type":"text"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"Why Swift for Playdate","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Why-Swift-for-Playdate"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/play.date","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" is a tiny handheld gaming console developed by "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/panic.com"},{"text":", featuring a Cortex M7 processor and a 400 by 240 1-bit display. Panic provides an SDK for building Playdate games in both C and Lua and is equipped with a Playdate Simulator.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Most Playdate games are traditionally written in Lua for ease of development, but can run into performance problems that necessitate the added complexity of using C."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Embedded Swift solves this problem by pairing high-level ergonomics with low-level performance, while also providing memory safety guarantees that improve productivity and eliminate a common source of bugs."}]},{"level":2,"text":"Get Started","anchor":"Get-Started","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To build and run the Swift Playdate examples included in this repository, you’ll need some additional tools. Specifically, you need a recent Swift nightly toolchain (built on 3\/7\/24 or later) and a copy of the Playdate SDK. For instructions on setting up your development environment, see "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/Playdate\/documentation\/Playdate\/DownloadingTh